  "prompt": "What are the causes of having itchy small blisters on my fingers?",
  "response": "Several conditions can cause itchy small blisters on fingers:\n\n1. Eczema (Dyshidrotic eczema)\n- Common cause of small, itchy blisters\n- Often affects hands and fingers\n- Triggered by stress, allergies, or moisture\n\n2. Contact Dermatitis\n- Allergic reaction to chemicals, metals, or irritants\n- Can cause blistering and itching\n- Common triggers: soaps, detergents, nickel\n\n3. Fungal Infections\n- Caused by fungi like ringworm\n- Can result in small, itchy blisters\n- Often spread through direct contact\n\n4. Pompholyx\n- Type of eczema causing small, fluid-filled blisters\n- Typically on palms and sides of fingers\n- Can be related to stress or allergies\n\n5. Herpes Simplex Virus\n- Can cause small, painful blisters\n- Contagious and may recur\n\n6. Scabies\n- Caused by tiny mites\n- Creates intensely itchy blisters\n- Spreads through skin-to-skin contact\n\n7. Hand, Foot, and Mouth Disease\n- Viral infection\n- Common in children\n- Causes small, painful blisters\n\nRecommendation: Consult a healthcare professional for accurate diagnosis and treatment.",
